			<ns0:name>bradc...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/110304265766688778552/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">NaCl requires an outer sandbox to satisfy our security requirements.

&lt;b&gt;- Where are we today?&lt;/b&gt;
The setuid sandbox by Julien Tinnes is in use for Chrome, and Neha Narula
has spent some time working on adapting it for NaCl and adapting NaCl for it. 

&lt;b&gt;- Why is this a problem?&lt;/b&gt;
NaCl requires defense in depth.

&lt;b&gt;- The proposed enhancement:&lt;/b&gt;
Confirm that the current setuid sandbox works for the NaCl sel_ldr, fixing
any issues that prevent this from being true.

&lt;b&gt;- Exit criteria:&lt;/b&gt;
The outer sandbox is on by default for NaCl-enabled Linux Chrome5 browsers.
The outer sandbox traps an attempt to make a disallowed system call from
the service runtime.

&lt;b&gt;- Anticipated impact:&lt;/b&gt;
Defense in depth.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-03-09T19:46:14.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-03-01T16:49:03.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
